COLL (CASE) Sustainability Literacy credit'], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 208', 'ENVIRONMENT AND SOCIETY', '30265', 'Closed', 'MW Monday, Wednesday 9:10 AM–11:40 AM', 'WB WEB', 'Julio Postigo', 0, NULL, 'Lecture', '3', 'BALLANTINE HALL', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Just as we shape the environment, the environment shapes us. From globalization to food production to climate change, learn how humans and environments interact.', ARRAY['IUB GenEd N&M credit - Natural Science
COLL (CASE) N&M Breadth of Inquiry credit
COLL (CASE) Sustainability Literacy credit'], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 237', 'MAPPING OUR WORLD: FROM MERCATOR TO MASHUPS', '1830', 'Class Status', 'TuTh Tuesday, Thursday 12:45 PM–2:00 PM', 'SB 015', 'Taehee Hwang', 1, NULL, 'Lecture', '3', 'STUDENT BUILDING (FRANCES MORG', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Mapping lets us visualize our world and see how patterns change across places. For example, we can analyze how a bike-share program changes commuting patterns, or how urban farming emerges in a transforming city. Students learn how to develop digital maps and interpret spatial processes while gaining valuable experience with GIS software.', ARRAY['IUB GenEd N&M credit - Natural Science
COLL (CASE) N&M Breadth of Inquiry credit'], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 304', 'PHYSICAL METEOROLOGY AND CLIMATOLOGY', '10078', 'Closed', 'MW Monday, Wednesday 11:10 AM–12:25 PM', 'SB 005', 'Scott Robeson', 0, NULL, 'Lecture', '3', 'STUDENT BUILDING (FRANCES MORG', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Provides an introduction to the physical basis of Earth''s atmosphere and climate system from global to local scales, emphasizing physical processes and properties. Analyzes surface energy and water balances in varied landscapes. Covers issues related to climate change.', ARRAY['COLL (CASE) N&M Breadth of Inquiry credit'], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 314', 'URBAN GEOGRAPHY', '12195', 'Class Status', 'TuTh Tuesday, Thursday 9:35 AM–10:50 AM', 'SB 005', 'Leiha Edmonds', 10, NULL, 'Lecture', '3', 'STUDENT BUILDING (FRANCES MORG', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Study and interpretation of urban spatial structures, policies and problems with an emphasis on geographic perspectives. Topics include urban housing markets, racial segregation, homelessness, and urban crime.', ARRAY['COLL (CASE) S&H Breadth of Inquiry credit'], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 315', 'ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION', '12204', 'Closed', 'MW Monday, Wednesday 2:20 PM–3:35 PM', 'AC C002', 'Rebecca Lave', 0, NULL, 'Lecture', '3', 'CEDAR HALL', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Explores the environmental impact of global population growth, natural resources utilization, and pollution. Examines current problems relating to energy consumption, farming practices, water use, resource development and deforestation from geologic and ecological perspectives. Strategies designed to avert predicted global catastrophe will be examined to determine success potential.', ARRAY['COLL (CASE) S&H Breadth of Inquiry credit
COLL (CASE) Sustainability Literacy credit'], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 336', 'ENVIRONMENTAL REMOTE SENSING', '3644', 'Class Status', 'TuTh Tuesday, Thursday 9:35 AM–10:50 AM', 'SB 221', 'Taehee Hwang', 6, NULL, 'Lecture', '3', 'STUDENT BUILDING (FRANCES MORG', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Fundamental principles involved in digital and analog remote sensing, including radiation character, instrumentation, and applications. Technologies of data collection, airborne and satellite platforms, and image interpretation.', ARRAY['COLL (CASE) N&M Breadth of Inquiry credit'], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 338', 'GEOGRAPHIC INFORMATION SYSTEMS', '34554', 'Class Status', 'MW Monday, Wednesday 12:45 PM–2:00 PM', 'SB 221', 'Yaqian He', 12, NULL, 'Lecture', '3', 'STUDENT BUILDING (FRANCES MORG', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Introduction to the principles and applications of computer-based geographic information systems (GIS).', ARRAY['COLL (CASE) N&M Breadth of Inquiry credit'], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 338', 'GEOGRAPHIC INFORMATION SYSTEMS', '10767', 'Closed', 'TuTh Tuesday, Thursday 11:10 AM–12:25 PM', 'SB 221', 'Yuri Kim', 0, NULL, 'Lecture', '3', 'STUDENT BUILDING (FRANCES MORG', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Introduction to the principles and applications of computer-based geographic information systems (GIS).', ARRAY['COLL (CASE) N&M Breadth of Inquiry credit'], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 352', 'FOOD AND POVERTY IN AMERICA', '12856', 'Closed', 'MW Monday, Wednesday 12:45 PM–2:00 PM', 'SB 005', 'Olga Kalentzidou', 0, NULL, 'Lecture', '3', 'STUDENT BUILDING (FRANCES MORG', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Course Description This course examines the experience of food insecurity in the USA, the role of poverty in food production and consumption, and the current mitigation strategies and social movements challenging the global food regime. Students will learn the differences and connections between concepts of food security, food justice, and food sovereignty. Relationships between food and gender, race, and ethnicity will be explored, along with the geographical and social concepts of food deserts and food choice.', ARRAY['COLL (CASE) S&H Breadth of Inquiry credit
COLL (CASE) Culture Studies: Diversity in U.S.'], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 368', 'WATER IN THE MIDWEST', '30261', 'Closed', 'TuTh Tuesday, Thursday 11:10 AM–12:25 PM', 'SB 005', 'Darren Ficklin', 0, NULL, 'Lecture', '3', 'STUDENT BUILDING (FRANCES MORG', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Explores the science, politics, and ethics of water in the Midwest from the Bloomington campus to the Great Lakes and Mississippi River Basins. Critically examines such water issues as pollution, environmental justice, flooding, invasive species, agricultural and urban water demand, and effective regulation.', ARRAY['COLL (CASE) S&H Breadth of Inquiry credit'], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 379', 'TOPICS IN THE GEOGRAPHY OF FOODS', '8840', 'Closed', 'Tu Tuesday 3:55 PM–6:25 PM', 'SB 017', 'Olga Kalentzidou', 0, NULL, 'Lecture', '3', 'STUDENT BUILDING (FRANCES MORG', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Introduction to major cuisines of different countries. Food knowledge and practical skills are acquired through reading and cooking. Students are expected to be active participants in the course through reading, cooking and tasting food. Includes the cooking of a 4-5 course meal each class.', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 438', 'ADVANCED GEOGRAPHIC INFORMATION SYSTEMS', '9348', 'Class Status', 'MW Monday, Wednesday 9:35 AM–10:50 AM', 'SB 221', 'Yuri Kim', 9, NULL, 'Lecture', '3', 'STUDENT BUILDING (FRANCES MORG', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Covers intermediate and advanced theory in geographic information science and spatial analysis using GIS software. Provides an in-depth look into this rapidly developing field and teaches the skills needed to construct, manage, and analyze data and models.', ARRAY['COLL (CASE) N&M Breadth of Inquiry credit'], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 440', 'TOPICS IN ENVIRONMENTAL GEOGRAPHY', '30195', 'Class Status', 'TuTh Tuesday, Thursday 12:45 PM–2:00 PM', 'SB 017', 'Nubia Beray Armond', 17, NULL, 'Lecture', '3', 'STUDENT BUILDING (FRANCES MORG', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Selected topics focus on the human dimensions of environmental change/conservation. Example focus topics: population-environment interactions, transport-environment interactions, and urban-environment interactions.', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 441', 'MIGRATION AND MOBILITY', '34543', 'Class Status', 'TuTh Tuesday, Thursday 12:45 PM–2:00 PM', 'SB 005', 'Ishan Ashutosh', 24, NULL, 'Lecture', '3', 'STUDENT BUILDING (FRANCES MORG', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Geographers are turning attention to the processes that drive, regulate and accompany various scales of movement, the politics of mobility, and the experience and effect of mobility. A better understanding of mobility helps them investigate processes like globalization, migration, tourism, homelessness, security and transport, international flows as well as micro-scale bodily movements in more nuanced ways.', ARRAY['COLL (CASE) S&H Breadth of Inquiry credit'], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 444', 'CLIMATE CHANGE IMPACTS', '30200', 'Closed', 'TuTh Tuesday, Thursday 2:20 PM–3:35 PM', 'SB 005', 'Darren Ficklin', 0, NULL, 'Lecture', '3', 'STUDENT BUILDING (FRANCES MORG', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Increasing concentrations of greenhouse gases are causing climate to change at an unprecedented rate. This course will explain how and why anthropogenic activity is causing climate to change, how this impacts society and options for adaptation and mitigation, plus the potential to reduce climate change through geoengineering.', ARRAY['COLL (CASE) N&M Breadth of Inquiry credit'], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 445', 'HOUSING STRUGGLES UNDER CAPITALISM', '14853', 'Class Status', 'Tu Tuesday 10:00 AM–12:30 PM', 'SB 017', 'Patricia Basile', 2, NULL, 'Seminar', '3', 'STUDENT BUILDING (FRANCES MORG', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Studies housing through a feminist political economy framework and analyzes the centrality of housing in multiple modalities of capital within the economy social and political contexts. Identifies and examines the struggles of racialized and dispossessed people and communities in the fight for and construction of alternative realities of housing.', ARRAY['COLL (CASE) Sustainability Literacy credit'], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 452', 'TREE-RING SCIENCE', '30263', 'Class Status', 'TuTh Tuesday, Thursday 10:25 AM–12:55 PM', 'SB 014', 'Justin Maxwell', 2, NULL, 'Lecture', '3', 'STUDENT BUILDING (FRANCES MORG', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Examines the science of dendrochronology. Developing a scientific understanding of the information recorded by trees is essential to our quest to better understand natural and human processes.', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 461', 'HUMAN DIMENSIONS OF GLOBAL ENVIRONMENTAL CHANGE', '13427', 'Class Status', 'M Monday 4:20 PM–6:50 PM', 'SB 005', 'Julio Postigo', 14, NULL, 'Lecture', '3', 'STUDENT BUILDING (FRANCES MORG', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Introduction to global environmental change (GEC), focusing on the human causes and consequences of biophysical transformations of land systems. Emphasis on socioeconomic, political, institutional, and environmental dimensions of land change; tropical forests, grasslands, and urbanizing areas; international environmental regimes; spatial methodologies in GEC research, and integrated approaches.', ARRAY['COLL (CASE) S&H Breadth of Inquiry credit'], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 469', 'FOOD AND GLOBAL POVERTY', '34559', 'Closed', 'MW Monday, Wednesday 9:35 AM–10:50 AM', 'SB 005', 'Annie Shattuck', 0, NULL, 'Seminar', '3', 'STUDENT BUILDING (FRANCES MORG', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'How is the production and consumption of food related to poverty and development? Explores how global food systems affect farmers, farmworkers, retailers and consumers; the ways scientific advances changed rural economies in the Third World; and the history of famine and contemporary food security issues.', ARRAY['COLL (CASE) S&H Breadth of Inquiry credit
COLL (CASE) Culture Studies: Global Civ & Culture
COLL (CASE) Sustainability Literacy credit'], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 474', 'SOLIDARITY ECONOMY IN LATIN AMERICA', '30189', 'Class Status', 'TuTh Tuesday, Thursday 3:55 PM–5:10 PM', 'SB 005', 'Patricia Basile', 3, NULL, 'Lecture', '3', 'STUDENT BUILDING (FRANCES MORG', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Traces the histories, practices, and realities of solidarity economies throughout Latin America. Considers solidarity economy as a broad eco-system of values, relationships, and activities that allow for the advancement of an alternative framework of development centered on equity, cooperation, solidarity, self-management, and democracy.', ARRAY['COLL (CASE) Culture Studies: Global Civ & Culture'], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 488', 'APPLIED SPATIAL STATISTICS', '10392', 'Class Status', 'M Monday 2:20 PM–3:35 PM', 'SB 005 SB 221', 'Scott Robeson', 11, NULL, 'Lecture', '3', 'STUDENT BUILDING (FRANCES MORG', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Extension of traditional statistical analysis to spatial data. Spatial means and spatial variances, the examination of differences in samples over space, spatial autocorrelation, nearest neighbor analysis, map comparison techniques. Emphasis is on practical applications.', ARRAY['COLL (CASE) N&M Breadth of Inquiry credit'], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 499', 'HONORS IN RESEARCH IN GEOGRAPHY', '5054', 'Class Status', NULL, NULL, 'Justin Maxwell, Terri Loyal', 2, NULL, 'Independent Study', '3', NULL, ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Training in research and scholarly writing, culminating in an honors thesis to be written under the direction of a faculty member. An oral examination of the thesis is conducted by two faculty members.', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 500', 'RESEARCH PROBLEMS IN GEOGRAPHY', '10103', 'Class Status', 'F Friday 9:10 AM–11:40 AM', 'SB 014', 'Ishan Ashutosh', 6, NULL, 'Lecture', '3', 'STUDENT BUILDING (FRANCES MORG', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Examination of current research areas and research problems in geography. Introduction to research design and research methods.', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 520', 'MIGRATION AND MOBILITY', '34544', 'Class Status', 'TuTh Tuesday, Thursday 12:45 PM–2:00 PM', 'SB 005', 'Ishan Ashutosh', 24, NULL, 'Lecture', '3', 'STUDENT BUILDING (FRANCES MORG', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Geographers are turning attention to processes that drive, regulate and accompany various scales of movement, politics of mobility, and the experience and effect of mobility. An understanding of mobility helps investigate processes like globalization, migration, tourism, homelessness, security and transport, international flows and micro-scale bodily movements in nuanced ways.', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 527', 'DEPARTMENT OF GEOGRAPHY COLLOQUIUM', '11860', 'Class Status', 'F Friday 3:10 PM–5:10 PM', 'SB 005', 'Justin Maxwell', 28, NULL, 'Colloquium', '1', 'STUDENT BUILDING (FRANCES MORG', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Weekly or bi-weekly talks by a variety of speakers both within and outside of IU. Each colloquium will feature a research presentation. If taken for credit, it is mandatory to attend the colloquium. Exceptions approved by the Geography Director of Graduate Studies.', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 532', 'PHYSICAL METEOROLOGY AND CLIMATOLOGY', '10079', 'Class Status', 'MW Monday, Wednesday 11:10 AM–12:25 PM', 'SB 005', 'Scott Robeson', 1, NULL, 'Lecture', '3', 'STUDENT BUILDING (FRANCES MORG', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Provides an introduction to the physical basis of Earth''s atmosphere and climate system from global to local scales, emphasizing physical processes and properties. Analyzes surface energy and water balances in varied landscapes. Covers issues related to climate change.', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 535', 'ENVIRONMENTAL REMOTE SENSING', '3645', 'Class Status', 'TuTh Tuesday, Thursday 9:35 AM–10:50 AM', 'SB 221', 'Taehee Hwang', 6, NULL, 'Lecture', '3', 'STUDENT BUILDING (FRANCES MORG', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Principles of remote sensing of the earth and its atmosphere, emphasizing satellite data in visible, infrared, and microwave portions of the electromagnetic spectrum. Emphasis on practical applications and digital image analysis. A satellite data analysis project is required.', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 538', 'GEOGRAPHIC INFORMATION SYSTEMS', '34555', 'Class Status', 'MW Monday, Wednesday 12:45 PM–2:00 PM', 'SB 221', 'Yaqian He', 2, NULL, 'Lecture', '3', 'STUDENT BUILDING (FRANCES MORG', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Overview of the principles and practices of Geographic Information Systems (GIS). Spatial data models, database design, introductory and intermediate GIS operations, and case studies of real-world GIS applications. Laboratory exercises will provide significant hands-on experience. Lecture and laboratory.', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 538', 'GEOGRAPHIC INFORMATION SYSTEMS', '10768', 'Closed', 'TuTh Tuesday, Thursday 11:10 AM–12:25 PM', 'SB 221', 'Yuri Kim', 0, NULL, 'Lecture', '3', 'STUDENT BUILDING (FRANCES MORG', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Overview of the principles and practices of Geographic Information Systems (GIS). Spatial data models, database design, introductory and intermediate GIS operations, and case studies of real-world GIS applications. Laboratory exercises will provide significant hands-on experience. Lecture and laboratory.', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 539', 'ADVANCED GEOGRAPHIC INFORMATION SYSTEMS', '9349', 'Class Status', 'MW Monday, Wednesday 9:35 AM–10:50 AM', 'SB 221', 'Yuri Kim', 7, NULL, 'Lecture', '3', 'STUDENT BUILDING (FRANCES MORG', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Intermediate and advanced topics in geographic information science and spatial analysis techniques using GIS software. This advanced course is for graduates who seek a greater understanding of this rapidly developing field and to learn how to construct, manage and analyze their own GIS data and models.', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 540', 'TOPICS IN ENVIRONMENTAL GEOGRAPHY', '30196', 'Class Status', 'TuTh Tuesday, Thursday 12:45 PM–2:00 PM', 'SB 017', 'Nubia Beray Armond', 17, NULL, 'Seminar', '3', 'STUDENT BUILDING (FRANCES MORG', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL, ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 544', 'CLIMATE CHANGE IMPACTS', '30201', 'Closed', 'TuTh Tuesday, Thursday 2:20 PM–3:35 PM', 'SB 005', 'Darren Ficklin', 0, NULL, 'Lecture', '3', 'STUDENT BUILDING (FRANCES MORG', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Increasing concentrations of greenhouse gases are causing climate to change at an unprecedented rate. This course will explain how and why anthropogenic activity is causing climate to change, how this impacts society and options for adaptation and mitigation, plus the potential to reduce climate change through geoengineering.', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 545', 'HOUSING STRUGGLES UNDER CAPITALISM', '15166', 'Class Status', 'Tu Tuesday 10:00 AM–12:30 PM', 'SB 017', 'Patricia Basile', 4, NULL, 'Seminar', '3', 'STUDENT BUILDING (FRANCES MORG', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Study housing through a feminist political economy framework, analyze the centrality of housing in multiple modalities of capital within the economy social and political contexts. Aim to identify and understand struggles of racialized and dispossessed people and communities in the fight for and construction of alternative realities of housing.', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 552', 'TREE-RING SCIENCE', '30264', 'Class Status', 'TuTh Tuesday, Thursday 10:25 AM–12:55 PM', 'SB 014', 'Justin Maxwell', 2, NULL, 'Lecture', '3', 'STUDENT BUILDING (FRANCES MORG', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Examines the science of dendrochronology. The primary focus will be the applications of the science, as ultimately the information recorded by the trees must be used in our quest to better understand natural and human processes.', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 560', 'GEOGRAPHY INTERNSHIP', '1831', 'Class Status', NULL, NULL, 'Justin Maxwell, Terri Loyal', 5, NULL, 'Independent Study', '1–4', NULL, ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Faculty-directed study of geographical problems based on an internship experience. Student''s area of placement must be related to major field of study. Student may complete more than one internship but the total credit cannot be more than 4 credit hours.', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 561', 'HUMAN DIMENSIONS OF GLOBAL ENVIRONMENTAL CHANGE', '13428', 'Class Status', 'M Monday 4:20 PM–6:50 PM', 'SB 005', 'Julio Postigo', 14, NULL, 'Seminar', '3', 'STUDENT BUILDING (FRANCES MORG', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Introduction of global environmental change (GEC), focusing on the human causes and consequences of biophysical transformations of land systems. Emphasis on socioeconomic, political, institutional and environmental dimensions of land change; tropical forests, grasslands and urbanizing areas; international environmental regimes; spatial methodologies in GEC research, and integrated approaches.', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 574', 'SOLIDARITY ECONOMY IN LATIN AMERICA', '35700', 'Class Status', 'TuTh Tuesday, Thursday 3:55 PM–5:10 PM', 'SB 005', 'Patricia Basile', 4, NULL, 'Lecture', '3', 'STUDENT BUILDING (FRANCES MORG', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'In this course, we seek to trace the histories, practices, and realities of solidarity economies throughout Latin America. We consider solidarity economy as a broad eco-system of values, relationships, and activities that allow for the advancement of an alternative framework of development centered on equity, cooperation, solidarity, self-management, and democracy.', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 588', 'APPLIED SPATIAL STATISTICS', '10393', 'Class Status', 'M Monday 2:20 PM–3:35 PM', 'SB 005 SB 221', 'Scott Robeson', 11, NULL, 'Lecture', '3', 'STUDENT BUILDING (FRANCES MORG', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Extension of Traditional statistical analysis to spatial data. Spatial means and spatial variances, the examination of differences in samples over space, spatial autocorrelation, nearest neighbor analysis, map comparison techniques. Emphasis on practical applications.', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 599', 'THESIS RESEARCH', '3119', 'Class Status', NULL, NULL, 'Justin Maxwell, Terri Loyal', 1, NULL, 'Research', '0', NULL, ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Master''s students who have enrolled in 30 or more hours of graduate course work applicable to the degree and who have completed all other requirements of the degree except the thesis of final project of performance may enroll in G599. Requires section authorization.', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 830', 'READINGS IN GEOGRAPHY', '10880', 'Class Status', NULL, NULL, 'Justin Maxwell, Terri Loyal', 5, NULL, 'Readings', '1–3', 'WEB-BASED CLASS', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Advanced courses in geography or closely related fields. Supervised readings on selected topics.', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 830', 'READINGS IN GEOGRAPHY', '1832', 'Class Status', NULL, NULL, 'Justin Maxwell, Terri Loyal', 7, NULL, 'Readings', '1–3', 'WEB-BASED CLASS', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Advanced courses in geography or closely related fields. Supervised readings on selected topics.', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 830', 'READINGS IN GEOGRAPHY', '3201', 'Class Status', NULL, NULL, 'Justin Maxwell, Terri Loyal', 4, NULL, 'Readings', '1–3', 'WEB-BASED CLASS', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Advanced courses in geography or closely related fields. Supervised readings on selected topics.', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 830', 'READINGS IN GEOGRAPHY', '3208', 'Class Status', NULL, NULL, 'Justin Maxwell, Terri Loyal', 6, NULL, 'Readings', '1–3', 'WEB-BASED CLASS', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Advanced courses in geography or closely related fields. Supervised readings on selected topics.', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 830', 'READINGS IN GEOGRAPHY', '9998', 'Closed', NULL, 'WB WEB', 'Justin Maxwell, Terri Loyal', 0, NULL, 'Readings', '1–3', 'WEB-BASED CLASS', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Advanced courses in geography or closely related fields. Supervised readings on selected topics.', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 831', 'ADVANCED RESEARCH IN GEOGRAPHY', '1833', 'Class Status', NULL, NULL, 'Justin Maxwell, Terri Loyal', 1, NULL, 'Independent Study', '1–6', NULL, ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Individual research.', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 840', 'RESEARCH IN GEOGRAPHY', '1834', 'Class Status', NULL, NULL, 'Justin Maxwell, Terri Loyal', 1, NULL, 'Independent Study', '1–6', NULL, ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL, ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 840', 'RESEARCH IN GEOGRAPHY', '3202', 'Class Status', NULL, NULL, 'Justin Maxwell, Terri Loyal', 6, NULL, 'Independent Study', '1–6', NULL, ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL, ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 845', 'MASTERS PAPERS', '1835', 'Class Status', NULL, NULL, 'Justin Maxwell, Terri Loyal', 5, NULL, 'Independent Study', '1–6', NULL, ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Research papers under the supervision of faculty. Graduate students in the MS in Geographic Information Science program who choose the research papers option will develop two research papers under the guidance of their graduate advisor (IUPUI faculty member) and two other faculty members chosen in consultation with the advisor. The research paper topics will be related to the field of Geographic Information Science in their focus and methods.', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 850', 'MASTERS THESIS', '1836', 'Class Status', NULL, NULL, 'Justin Maxwell, Terri Loyal', 5, NULL, 'Independent Study', '1–6', NULL, ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Directed research and writing under the supervision of a faculty committee.', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 860', 'PH D THESIS', '1837', 'Class Status', NULL, NULL, 'Justin Maxwell, Terri Loyal', 8, NULL, 'Independent Study', '1–12', NULL, ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL, ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 860', 'PH D THESIS', '6994', 'Class Status', NULL, NULL, 'Justin Maxwell, Terri Loyal', 5, NULL, 'Independent Study', '1–12', NULL, ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL, ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOG-G 901', 'ADVANCED RESEARCH', '1838', 'Class Status', NULL, NULL, 'Justin Maxwell, Terri Loyal', 3, NULL, 'Research', '6', NULL, ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Available to graduate students who have completed all course requirements for their doctorates, have passed doctoral qualifying examinations, and have the requisite number of degree credit hours, this course provides the advanced research student with a forum for sharing ideas and problems under the supervision of a senior researcher.', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOG-X 473', 'INTERNSHIP - GEOGRAPHICAL ANALYSIS', '7112', 'Class Status', NULL, NULL, 'Justin Maxwell, Terri Loyal', 5, NULL, 'Internship', '1–6', NULL, ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Supervised field experience in geography, normally in conjunction with approved work at a government agency or private firm. Requires 45 hours of work per 1 credit hour.', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOG-X 490', 'UNDERGRADUATE READINGS AND RESEARCH IN GEOGRAPHY', '7114', 'Class Status', NULL, NULL, 'Justin Maxwell, Terri Loyal', 5, NULL, 'Independent Study', '1–3', NULL, ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Individual readings and research in geography.', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOG-X 490', 'UNDERGRADUATE READINGS AND RESEARCH IN GEOGRAPHY', '7235', 'Class Status', NULL, NULL, 'Justin Maxwell, Terri Loyal', 6, NULL, 'Independent Study', '1–3', NULL, ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Individual readings and research in geography.', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOG-X 490', 'UNDERGRADUATE READINGS AND RESEARCH IN GEOGRAPHY', '7236', 'Class Status', NULL, NULL, 'Justin Maxwell, Terri Loyal', 3, NULL, 'Independent Study', '1–3', NULL, ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Individual readings and research in geography.', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GEOL-G 540', 'PHYSICAL METEOROLOGY, CLIMATE, AND PALEOCLIMATE', '10026', 'Class Status', 'MW Monday, Wednesday 11:10 AM–12:25 PM', 'SB 005', 'Scott Robeson', 4, NULL, 'Lecture', '3', 'STUDENT BUILDING (FRANCES MORG', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Topics span multiple scales of atmospheric processes including past/recent/projected climate change, weather forecasting, severe weather, and surface energy budgets. Students gain knowledge concerning physical processes and properties of Earth''s atmosphere and acquire skills used to study and quantify atmospheric processes through problem solving with models and remote sensing data.', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], NULL),
    ('GER-E 122', 'FAIRY TALES FROM THE GRIMM BROTHERS TO TODAY', '7164', 'Class Status', 'TuTh Tuesday, Thursday 12:45 PM–2:00 PM', 'GA 1122', 'Susanne Even', 1, NULL, 'Lecture', '3', 'GLOBAL & INTERNATIONAL STUDIES', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Introduction to Germanic fairy tales. Some of the world''s most famous fairy tales are examined in their historical and cultural contexts and read for their contemporary significance. Promotes analysis of European culture revealed in these tales.', ARRAY['IUB GenEd World Culture credit
COLL (CASE) A&H Breadth of Inquiry credit
COLL (CASE) Culture Studies: Global Civ & Culture'], NULL),
    ('GER-E 141', 'AMSTERDAM', '14470', 'Class Status', 'TuTh Tuesday, Thursday 3:55 PM–5:10 PM', 'GA 0003', 'Frane Burazer', 2, NULL, 'Lecture', '3', 'GLOBAL & INTERNATIONAL STUDIES', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'General introduction to Dutch culture, focusing mostly on Amsterdam and its influence upon societies in and around the world. Emphasizes contemporary issues based on events in the past. May include a study of liberalism, policies, World War II, Anne Frank, water management, and trends in home design and architecture. Taught in English.', ARRAY['IUB GenEd World Culture credit
COLL (CASE) S&H Breadth of Inquiry credit'], NULL),
    ('GER-E 162', 'SCANDINAVIAN CULTURE', '13859', 'Closed', 'TuTh Tuesday, Thursday 3:55 PM–5:10 PM', 'GA 1122', 'Gergana May', 0, NULL, 'Lecture', '3', 'GLOBAL & INTERNATIONAL STUDIES', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Introduces Scandinavian cultural history from the region''s unique position as an ''outsider'' living in the outskirts of Europe and in close proximity to nature. Studies the Viking expansion, Icelandic sagas, traditional folk culture and its transformation into modern-day individual expression, indigenous modes of expression, contemporary literature and film, and current political and social trends.', ARRAY['IUB GenEd World Culture credit
COLL (CASE) A&H Breadth of Inquiry credit
COLL (CASE) Culture Studies: Global Civ & Culture'], NULL),
    ('GER-E 212', 'MULTICULTURAL GERMANY', '15037', 'Class Status', 'TuTh Tuesday, Thursday 9:35 AM–10:50 AM', 'GA 0007', 'Irit Dekel', 1, NULL, 'Lecture', '3', 'GLOBAL & INTERNATIONAL STUDIES', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Humanistic treatment of Germany in the context of plural democracies open to immigration and cultural diversity. Topics range from the discussion of "welcome culture" vs. "guiding culture"; post-migrant and post-colonial arts and literatures; memorialization and exhibition of the past and present; changing norms and their aesthetic and social expressions.', ARRAY['IUB GenEd A&H credit'], NULL),
    ('GER-E 212', 'MULTICULTURAL GERMANY', '11508', 'Closed', 'MW Monday, Wednesday 3:55 PM–5:10 PM', 'BH 221', 'Dov-Ber Kerler', 0, NULL, 'Lecture', '3', 'GLOBAL & INTERNATIONAL STUDIES', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Humanistic treatment of Germany in the context of plural democracies open to immigration and cultural diversity. Topics range from the discussion of "welcome culture" vs. "guiding culture"; post-migrant and post-colonial arts and literatures; memorialization and exhibition of the past and present; changing norms and their aesthetic and social expressions.', ARRAY['IUB GenEd A&H credit'], NULL),
    ('GER-G 100', 'BEGINNING GERMAN I', '1839', 'Class Status', 'MTuWTh Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday 8:00 AM–8:50 AM', 'BH 133', 'Clara Martinez Zuviria', 1, NULL, 'Drill', '4', 'BALLANTINE HALL', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Introduction to present-day German and to selected aspects of the cultures of German-speaking countries. Introduction to German grammatical forms and their functions. Development of listening comprehension, simple speaking proficiency, controlled reading skills and simple written compositions. Active oral participation required.', ARRAY['IUB GenEd World Language class'], NULL),
    ('GER-G 100', 'BEGINNING GERMAN I', '1841', 'Class Status', 'MTuWTh Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday 10:25 AM–11:15 AM', 'BH 245', 'Clara Martinez Zuviria', 11, NULL, 'Drill', '4', 'BALLANTINE HALL', ARRAY[]::TEXT[], 'Introduction to present-day German and to selected aspects of the cultures of German-speaking countries. Introduction to German grammatical forms and their functions. Development of listening comprehension, simple speaking proficiency, controlled reading skills and simple written compositions. Active oral participation required.', ARRAY['IUB GenEd World Language class'], NULL),
